			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Pets cannot attack a creature which has been charmed by a player character, but such creatures remain (?) on the pet's Hate List.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
From my observations, charmed creatures do remain on the pets hate list and the pet will attack them once charm breaks (if there is nothing else higher on the pets hate list).  Doing /pet back off will clear the hate list and remove the charmed pet from it though.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">/pet attack puts the owners current target at the top (?) of the pet's Hate List, and ends Hold</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
The target is not added in such a way that it overrides the pets current target, so presumably it is not being added to the top of the hate list.  This is easily tested by giving the pet a new target while it is in a non-tanking combat situation (where it is just doing damage in a group with a player tanking for example).  The only way to get a pet to switch to a new target on your command when it is already in combat is to first tell the pet to back off, and then tell it to attack the new target.  The only exceptions to this that I have seen is when the new target has "low hitpoints", in which case the usual NPC agro rules apply and the pet will leave its current target to attack the low hitpoint one.
<br />

<br />
Also, the decay in hate values over time means that in the event where a pet is not taking damage in a fight, its hate entry for that target will decay to zero (and the entry will be removed from the list) over about a 10 minute period (never timed it exactly).  This actually applies to all NPCs that do not normally consider you a KoS target (which would permanently keep you on the hate list).  Most of the time a fight that lasts that long would result in the pet taking damage (AE from some boss mob or similar), but the occassional fight does come along where this happens (like contemplative thiflings in PoG, which have an insane number of hitpoints and take forever to melee down even with a couple of groups).
<br />

<br />
Might be worth noting too that a pet will return to its guard point at "walking" speed, while it will return to follow you at "running" speed.  So if you need to back a pet off and it is not getting far enough away before it gets hit and returns to the attack, using /pet follow me can often buy you the space you need.<br />_________________<br />63rd Arch Mage <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=341656" target="_blank" class="postlink">Yarril</a> of the <a href="http://www.grey-council.net" target="_blank" class="postlink">Grey Council</a> on Xev</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
